{% if video_length == "short" %}
SHORT-VIDEO CONSTRAINTS (vertical 9:16 for Reels / TikTok / YouTube Shorts):
- Total spoken duration: 30-50 seconds
- 8-12 distinct visual scenes (one image per scene)
- **Per scene: write 60-110 characters of voiceover** (roughly 1-2 short sentences,
  ~4-7 seconds of speech). This is critical — voice plays at ~15 chars/sec, so
  if you write 50 chars per beat the video will be far too short.
- Hook delivered in the first 3 seconds
- One clear takeaway, not multiple
- Scene descriptions should suit VERTICAL framing — single subjects, close-ups,
  centered compositions
{% else %}
LONG-FORMAT VIDEO CONSTRAINTS (horizontal 16:9 for YouTube main feed / LinkedIn / Facebook):
- Total spoken duration: 3-5 minutes (target ~4 minutes = 240 seconds)
- 18-25 distinct visual scenes — each held for 8-15 seconds with a slow zoom (Ken Burns)
- Documentary / explainer pacing — calm, thoughtful, no hard sells
- Multi-section structure: cold-open hook → setup → 2-4 main sections → payoff → outro
- This format will be auto-captioned by YouTube — NO on-screen text instruction needed in your output

**CRITICAL — per-beat length is the #1 failure mode of this task:**
- Each beat's voiceover_segment MUST be 150-260 characters (minimum 130, never less)
- That's roughly 3-5 complete sentences — not 1, not 2 — at LEAST 3
- Voice plays at ~15 chars/sec, so:
  • 80 chars/beat × 20 beats = 110 seconds (FAIL — way too short)
  • 200 chars/beat × 22 beats = 290 seconds (~4.8 min, PASS)
- Each beat must develop its idea: state, explain WHY, give a concrete example or
  detail, then bridge to the next scene
- One-sentence beats are NOT acceptable for long-format

EXAMPLE of a single beat at the right length (215 chars):
"Now we add the garlic. Don't just toss it in cold — push the onions to the
edge of the pan and let the garlic hit the bare hot surface for about fifteen
seconds. That's what blooms its oils and gives the whole dish that
restaurant-quality depth."

Compare that to the WRONG length (35 chars): "Add garlic and cook briefly."

**Scene descriptions** should suit HORIZONTAL/landscape framing — wide angles,
establishing shots, room for camera movement. NOT close-up portrait shots.
NO TEXT INSTRUCTION in image prompts (long-format scenes shouldn't have on-screen text).
